    content:
      '<div class="writing">\n <h3>Rylands Library Papyrus P52 overview</h3>\n\n <p class="first">The <em>Rylands Library Papyrus P52</em> is a fragment from a Greek papyrus codex. The front contains parts of seven lines from <span class="scripture">John 18:31–33</span>, and the back contains parts of seven lines from <span class="scripture">John:37–38</span>.</p>\n\n <p>Although there is debate on the subject, it is generally dated to the first half of the second century, or sometime between 100-150 CE.</p>\n\n <h3>What is the significance of the Rylands Library Papyrus P52?</h3>\n\n <p class="first">The Rylands manuscript helps establish an early date for the writing of the gospels. If the book of John was written in the first half of the second century, then that means that the other gospels would have been written even earlier than that. This manuscript gives us greater confidence in the reliable transmission of the Bible throughout history.</p>\n</div>',
